        "text": "2 Chronicles 11:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The \"rock\" marks the limestone cliffs of the region (Stanley's 'Sinai and Palestine,' pp. 254-259, edit. 1866). We read of it, as David's refuge (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 22:1, 2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). From our present passage, and its parallel we should have concluded that it could not have been far from Bethlehem. In this sense Dr. Thomson ('The Land and the Book,' pp. 606, 607) refers to the tradition that fixes the cave at a spot now called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Khureitun",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", between Bethlehem and the Dead Sea, and says, \"Leaving our horses in charge of wild Arabs, and taking one Arab for a guide, we started for the cave, having a fearful gorge below, gigantic cliffs above, and the path winding along a shelf of the rock, narrow enough to make the nervous among us shudder. At length from a great rock, hanging on the edge of this shelf, we sprang by a long leap into a low window, which opened into the perpendicular face of the cliff. We were then within the hold of David, and creeping half-doubled through a narrow crevice for a few rods, we stood beneath the dark vault of the first grand chamber of this mysterious and oppressive cavern. Our whole collection of lights did little more than make the damp darkness visible. After groping about as long as we had Lime to spare, we returned to the light of day, fully convinced that, with David and his lion-hearted followers inside, all the strength of Israel under Saul could not have forced an entrance, and would not even have attempted it.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "host",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". For this word \"host\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "מַחֲגֵה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the parallel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") has the \"life of the Philistines\" (but the Authorized Version, the \"troop of\"), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the beasts and cattle of the Philistines. So also the Syriac Version translates, The Septuagint shows in this place ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "παρεμβολή",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and in Samuel ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τὰγμα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "valley of Rephaim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The situation of this notable valley is not certain. Yet there can be little doubt, in spite of Furst ('Handwortbuch,' 2:383), who supposes a situation north-west of Jerusalem, that it must be near Bethlehem, and therefore south-west of the city. The word employed Here for \"valley\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עִמֶק",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " should mark an ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "enclosed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " one. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Rephaim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " means \"giants.\" Hence our Authorized Version, \"The valley of Hinnom westward, which is at the end of the valley of the giants northward\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
